anthony norcia ph d vision and neurodevelopment lab stanford university vision and neurodevelopment lab svndl home people research for participants anthony norcia ph d secondary links lab members anthony norcia ph d benoit cottereau ph d claudia arrighi faraz farzin ph d francesca pei phd justin ales ph d rich miller ph d stefano baldassi phd vladimir vildavski ph d publications autism research infant vision research contacts and directions home anthony norcia ph d position professor research tony norcia received his bachelor's degree in psychology at the university of minnesota in 1975 and his ph d in physiological psychology from stanford in 1981 he did post doctoral work under lorrin riggs at brown he then spent 28 years at the smith kettlewell eye research institute before joining the stanford faculty in 2010 he is a fellow of the association for research in vision and ophthalmology and is a winner of the walt and lilly disney amblyopia research award from research to prevent blindness view his cv anthony norcia new articles december 2011 impaired visual decision making in individuals with amblyopia farzin f norcia am j vis 2011 dec 6 11 14 pii 6 doi 10.1167 11.14 6 print 2011 resolution of spatial and temporal visual attention in infants with fragile x syndrome farzin f rivera sm whitney d brain 2011 nov 134 pt 11 3355 68 increasing the accuracy of electromagnetic inverses using functional area source correlation constraints cottereau br ales jm norcia am hum brain mapp 2011 sep 21 spatio temporal templates of transient attention revealed by classification images megna n rocchi f baldassi s 2011 vision research in press user login username password request new password footer copyright 2010 svndl powered by drupal an open source content management system
